    <!-- Food Section -->
    <section id="food" class="px-6 py-24 relative">
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-transparent to-gray-100 dark:to-gray-900 z-0"></div>
        
        <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto relative z-10">
            <div class="text-center mb-16 scroll-trigger">
                <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Flavors of the East</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
                    East Indian cuisine is characterized by its subtle flavors, masterful use of seafood, and the distinctive 
                    influence of mustard oil. From sweet delicacies to hearty rice dishes, the region offers a diverse palette of tastes.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-10">
                <!-- Rasgulla Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="rasagulla.jpeg" alt="Rasgulla" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Rasgulla</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Spongy cheese balls soaked in sugar syrup, a beloved Bengali sweet.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Origin Controversy</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                The origin of rasgulla sparked one of India's most famous culinary disputes between West Bengal and Odisha. 
                                While Bengal claims Nabin Chandra Das invented it in 1868, Odisha asserts it evolved from the temple 
                                offering "Kheer Mohana" in Puri, dating back at least 600 years. In 2017, West Bengal received the 
                                Geographical Indication (GI) tag for "Banglar Rasgulla" while in 2018, Odisha received the GI tag for 
                                "Odisha Rasgulla," acknowledging both variants as distinct.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Cultural Significance</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                In Bengali culture, rasgulla is more than just a sweet – it's a symbol of celebration. It's traditionally 
                                offered as "mukh mishti" (sweetening the mouth) at the end of important ceremonies. In Odisha, 
                                particularly at the Jagannath Temple, offering rasgulla to appease Goddess Lakshmi is a crucial part of 
                                the Rath Yatra festival, highlighting its religious significance.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Culinary Innovation</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                The creation of rasgulla demonstrates remarkable food science understanding. The cheesemakers discovered 
                                that heating chhana (cottage cheese) with semolina under precise conditions creates a spongy texture 
                                that can absorb sugar syrup. Modern variations include chocolate rasgulla, mango rasgulla, and even 
                                a vacuum-packed canned version that helped spread this regional delicacy worldwide.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Machher Jhol Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="fishfry.jpeg" alt="Bengali Fish Curry" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Machher Jhol</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Traditional Bengali fish curry with light, flavorful gravy.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">River-Influenced Cuisine</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Machher Jhol (fish curry) embodies the riverine identity of Bengal. With rivers like Hooghly, Padma, and 
                                numerous tributaries flowing through the region, fish became central to Bengali cuisine and culture. 
                                The traditional saying "Machhe Bhate Bangali" (Bengalis thrive on fish and rice) reflects this deep 
                                connection. Historically, different fish were associated with specific social occasions and seasons.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Culinary Technique</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                True Machher Jhol represents culinary precision. The key lies in the "panch phoron" (five-spice blend) 
                                tempered in mustard oil, creating a distinctive base flavor. The gravy is typically light, allowing the 
                                fish's natural flavors to shine. Different variations exist, from the simple "tel jhol" (with minimal 
                                spices) to the more complex "jhal jhol" (spicy variant with green chilies). The most prized fish for 
                                this dish is Rohu (Rui), though Katla and Hilsa are also used for special occasions.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Social Ritual</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                Serving Machher Jhol follows specific etiquette in traditional Bengali households. The fish head is 
                                offered to the most respected or eldest family member as a sign of honor. Meals are often served 
                                in a specific sequence, with fish curry coming after bitter vegetables (shukto) but before sweet 
                                dishes. During Bengali weddings, serving fish symbolizes prosperity and fertility for the newlyweds.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Litti Chokha Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="Litti-Chokha.jpeg" alt="Litti Chokha" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Litti Chokha</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Roasted wheat balls filled with spiced sattu, served with mashed vegetables.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Historical Resilience</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Litti Chokha's origins demonstrate remarkable adaptation to challenging circumstances. During the 1857 
                                Indian rebellion against British rule, this dish became crucial for freedom fighters. Its long shelf life, 
                                no need for utensils, and high nutritional content made it ideal for soldiers on the move. The dish could 
                                be prepared in advance, buried in sand, and cooked slowly with minimal fire, preventing detection by 
                                British forces.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Nutritional Wisdom</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                At the heart of Litti is sattu – roasted gram flour that is remarkably nutritious. Rich in protein, fiber, 
                                and complex carbohydrates, sattu provides sustained energy and was ideal for regions prone to food scarcity. 
                                The accompanying chokha – made from roasted and mashed vegetables like eggplant, potatoes, and tomatoes – 
                                adds essential vitamins and minerals. This balanced combination developed intuitively in a resource-limited 
                                environment, showcasing the nutritional wisdom embedded in traditional cuisines.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Regional Identity</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                While primarily associated with Bihar, Litti Chokha enjoys variations across eastern India, including 
                                parts of Jharkhand and eastern Uttar Pradesh. In Bihar, it remains a cultural cornerstone, celebrated in 
                                folk songs and regional literature. Despite its humble origins, it has transcended class boundaries to 
                                become a unifying dish enjoyed by all social strata. Recent years have seen gourmet adaptations in urban 
                                restaurants, though purists insist that authentic Litti must be roasted over cow dung cakes for its 
                                distinctive smoky flavor.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Pitha Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="pist.jpg" alt="Assamese Pitha" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Pitha</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Traditional rice cakes from Assam and Northeast India with various fillings.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Harvest Celebration</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Pitha is intrinsically linked to harvest festivals across Northeast India, particularly during Bihu in Assam 
                                and Poush Parbon in Bengal. These rice cakes celebrate the first rice harvest of the season, symbolizing 
                                prosperity and gratitude. The preparation of various pitha types is not just cooking but a ceremonial 
                                activity where women gather to make them collectively, sharing stories and strengthening community bonds.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Diverse Varieties</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                The genius of pitha lies in its versatility. Different regions have developed dozens of varieties:
                                <br>- Til Pitha: Rice flour pancakes with sesame filling
                                <br>- Ghila Pitha: Deep-fried rice flour dough shaped like donuts
                                <br>- Sunga Pitha: Rice batter cooked inside bamboo tubes
                                <br>- Bhapa Pitha: Steamed with coconut fillings
                                <br>- Chitoi Pitha: Soft spongy rice cakes with tiny holes
                                Each type requires specific techniques passed down through generations, with cooking methods ranging from 
                                steaming and frying to roasting and baking.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Cultural Preservation</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                In modern times, pitha-making has become a symbol of cultural preservation for communities from Northeast 
                                India. As urbanization changes traditional lifestyles, seasonal pitha-making workshops and competitions 
                                have emerged to pass skills to younger generations. The dish represents the agricultural heritage, 
                                sophisticated food preservation techniques, and the use of locally available ingredients – serving as 
                                an edible archive of Northeast Indian cultural knowledge.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
    
    <!-- Festival Section -->
    <section id="festivals" class="px-6 py-24 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-900 relative">
        <div class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-full h-32 bg-gradient-to-b from-white dark:from-gray-900 to-transparent z-10"></div>
        
        <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto relative z-20">
            <div class="text-center mb-16 scroll-trigger">
                <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Celebrations of East India</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
                    East India's festivals blend religious devotion with artistic expression, historical commemoration, and seasonal cycles.
                    These celebrations showcase the region's deep cultural roots and vibrant community spirit.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-10">
                <!-- Durga Puja Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden shadow-special">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="durga.jpeg" alt="Durga Puja" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Durga Puja</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Bengal's greatest festival celebrating the goddess Durga's victory over evil.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Artistic Phenomenon</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Durga Puja has evolved into one of the world's largest art festivals. Each year, thousands of pandals 
                                (temporary structures) transform Kolkata and other Bengali cities into open-air galleries. These pandals 
                                showcase incredible creativity with themes ranging from ancient temples to contemporary social issues. 
                                In 2021, UNESCO recognized Durga Puja on its Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of 
                                Humanity, acknowledging its unique blend of religion, art, and communal harmony.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Historical Evolution</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                While the worship of Goddess Durga dates back centuries, the grand public celebration began during 
                                18th-century Bengal. The first recorded grand community puja (sarbojanin) was organized by twelve friends 
                                in Guptipara, Hooghly, in 1790. During British colonial rule, wealthy landlords (zamindars) started organizing 
                                lavish pujas. The festival took on nationalist overtones during India's freedom struggle, with community 
                                pujas becoming expressions of cultural identity and resistance. Post-independence, it evolved into the 
                                spectacular carnival-like celebration seen today.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Economic Engine</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                Durga Puja drives a massive seasonal economy worth billions of rupees. It creates a complex ecosystem 
                                involving artisans, decorators, lighting specialists, clothing retailers, food vendors, and the 
                                entertainment industry. The festival provides critical income for thousands of traditional craftspeople, 
                                particularly the kumors (clay artisans) who create the elaborate idols. In recent years, corporate 
                                sponsorship has transformed many pujas into major commercial events with budgets sometimes exceeding 
                                ₹1 crore (approximately $120,000) for a single pandal.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Bihu Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="bihu.jpg" alt="Bihu Dance" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Bihu</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Assam's most important festival marking seasonal transitions and agricultural cycles.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Three Seasonal Celebrations</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Bihu is actually a set of three distinct festivals marking Assam's agricultural calendar:
                                <br>- Bohag Bihu (Rongali Bihu): Celebrated in April, it marks the Assamese New Year and spring season when 
                                fields are prepared for cultivation. It's the most exuberant of the three.
                                <br>- Magh Bihu (Bhogali Bihu): January's harvest festival involves community feasting and bonfires.
                                <br>- Kati Bihu (Kongali Bihu): October's somber festival happens during the lean agricultural period, with 
                                lamps lit in paddy fields to guide the spirits of prosperity.
                                This triple celebration demonstrates Assamese society's deep connection to agricultural rhythms.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Cultural Expression</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                The vibrant Bihu dance embodies Assamese cultural identity. Performed with dynamic movements and 
                                accompanied by traditional instruments like the dhol (drum), pepa (buffalo horn pipe), and gagana 
                                (bamboo instrument), it represents youthful energy and fertility. Originally performed in rice fields to 
                                celebrate harvest, the dance features intricate hand gestures and rapid hip movements. Young men and 
                                women dance separately and then together, symbolizing the community's wishes for agricultural prosperity.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Communal Harmony</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                Bihu holds significance as a unifying cultural force in Assam's diverse society. Though originally an 
                                indigenous pre-Hindu tradition, it is now celebrated by people of all religions and ethnic backgrounds 
                                in Assam, including Muslims, Christians, and various tribal communities. During a time when regional 
                                identities are sometimes under pressure, Bihu serves as a cultural anchor that transcends religious 
                                boundaries while preserving local heritage against homogenizing globalizing influences.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Rath Yatra Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="rath.jpeg" alt="Rath Yatra" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Rath Yatra</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Odisha's ancient chariot festival dedicated to Lord Jagannath.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Engineering Marvel</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                The Rath Yatra features three massive wooden chariots that are rebuilt every year using traditional 
                                techniques without formal blueprints. The largest chariot, Lord Jagannath's Nandighosha, stands 45 feet 
                                tall and has 16 wheels. These chariots represent remarkable engineering knowledge passed down through 
                                generations of craftsmen called Maharanas. The construction follows precise rituals starting on Akshaya 
                                Tritiya day, taking exactly 58 days to complete. Each chariot requires hundreds of logs and thousands of 
                                man-hours with no modern tools used – a testament to ancient Indian engineering excellence.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Historical Continuity</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                The Rath Yatra of Puri is possibly the world's oldest continuously celebrated festival. Historical records 
                                confirm it has been observed annually since at least the 12th century CE without interruption, even during 
                                foreign invasions, natural disasters, and pandemics (with modifications during COVID-19). The earliest mention 
                                of the chariot procession appears in the Skanda Purana, and carvings at the Konark Sun Temple (13th century) 
                                depict the festival. This remarkable continuity makes it a living museum of religious and cultural practices.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Global Influence</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                The Rath Yatra has influenced world culture in unexpected ways. The English word "juggernaut" (meaning 
                                unstoppable force) derives from Jagannath's chariot, as described by British colonizers who witnessed 
                                devotees' fervor during the festival. The ISKCON movement popularized the festival globally, with over 
                                175 cities worldwide now hosting their own Rath Yatras. During the festival, Puri exemplifies remarkable 
                                social inclusivity – it's one of the rare occasions in traditional Hindu practice where caste distinctions 
                                are officially suspended, as devotees of all backgrounds can touch the deities' chariots.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Chhath Puja Card -->
                <div class="card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <div class="relative h-60 overflow-hidden">
                        <img src="chath.jpeg" alt="Chhath Puja" class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 hover:scale-110">
                    </div>
                    <div class="p-6 expandable-card">
                        <div class="flex justify-between items-center mb-4">
                            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold">Chhath Puja</h3>
                            <button class="expand-btn text-accent">
                                <i class="fas fa-chevron-down rotate-icon"></i>
                            </button>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                            Bihar's ancient festival worshipping the sun god and celebrating water sources.
                        </p>
                        <div class="hidden-content">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Ancient Solar Worship</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Chhath Puja predates written history, with some scholars tracing it to the Vedic period when the sun was 
                                worshipped as the source of all energy. Historical evidence suggests it was observed in the ancient Magadh 
                                kingdom (modern-day Bihar) at least 3,000 years ago. The festival is dedicated primarily to Surya (the sun god) 
                                and Chhathi Maiya (believed to be Surya's sister), making it one of the rare Hindu celebrations where a female 
                                deity is the primary focus. The rituals show striking parallels to ancient Egyptian and Mesopotamian solar 
                                worship practices.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Environmental Significance</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
                                Chhath Puja embodies profound environmental wisdom. The rituals purify water bodies and emphasize harmony 
                                with nature. Devotees (vratins) stand in water for extended periods, offering prayers at sunrise and sunset – 
                                the two transitional periods when solar ultraviolet radiation naturally purifies water. The strict fasting and 
                                use of natural materials like bamboo, clay, and biodegradable substances demonstrate sustainable practices 
                                long before modern environmentalism. The festival essentially creates community accountability for maintaining 
                                clean water sources, with rivers and ponds specially cleaned before celebrations.
                            </p>
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-lg mt-4 mb-2">Women's Central Role</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
                                Chhath Puja uniquely places women at the center of religious observance. The main vratins (observers) are 
                                typically women who undertake demanding rituals including a 36-hour waterless fast while standing for long 
                                periods in water. This challenging observance highlights women's spiritual authority and endurance. Men 
                                assume supportive roles, often caring for children and domestic responsibilities during the festival – a 
                                notable role reversal in traditional societies. The festival is also remarkable for its absence of Brahmin 
                                priests; women perform all rituals independently, representing an indigenous tradition that empowers female 
                                religious leadership.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
    
